INFO 11-14 21:00:32 [logger.py:43] Received request chatcmpl-d26ac58ba4c2424b9c82dce091d5dc04: prompt: '<s>[INST] Hi, here\'s some system prompt: hi.For user 46, here are some other context: hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi.\n\nPlease respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: I want you to act as an interviewer. I will be the candidate and you will ask me the interview questions for the Front-end position. I want you to only reply as the interviewer. Do not write all the conservation at once. I want you to only do the interview with me. Ask me the questions and wait for my answers. Do not write explanations. Ask me the questions one by one like an interviewer does and wait for my answers. My first sentence is "Hi"\nAnswer: Great, let\'s get started. Hi, Can you tell me a little about your background and experience as a front-end developer?\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: I\'ve been working as a front-end since 2017, mostly using reactjs and nextjs.\nAnswer: What specific projects have you worked on that you\'re most proud of and why?\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: I\'m most proud of one I led in 2021. It was commodities trading application where I led a team of 6 other engineers.\nAnswer: Can you tell me about your experience working with a team? How do you handle conflicts within the team or with stakeholders?\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: Sure. I\'m usually very good at working with team. I also have experiences working on multicultural environment where conflicts might raise just because people have different cultural backgrounds. I believe in talking with the team or stakeholders when we have a problem. An open communication is always good to solve conflicts.\nAnswer: How do you keep yourself updated on the latest advancements in front-end development?\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: I follow product releases notes, documentations as well as people who are more experienced than me.\nAnswer: Can you give an example of a particularly challenging problem you\'ve had to solve in your previous work as a front-end developer and how you went about solving it? [/INST] Sure, I\'d be happy to help! Here are my responses to each of the five conversations:\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\n\nAnswer: Great, let\'s get started. Hi, Can you tell me a little about your background and experience as a front-end developer?\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\n\nAnswer: What specific projects have you worked on that you\'re most proud of and why?\n\n--- Conversation </s><s>[INST] Please respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: Sure. I have to create a desktop application and train a mobile team and keep updating the mobile application at the same time. I used a similar technology on the desktop app to be able to handle everything without increasing the resources necessary to get the job done.\nAnswer: Great, Can you tell me about your experience working with a CSS preprocessor like SASS or LESS?\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: Sure. I worked a bit with SASS. But, to be honest, these day I prefer using tailwind css.\nAnswer: What\'s your process when it comes to debugging and troubleshooting issues that come up in your code?\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: It dependes on the issue. Simples things can be debugged by just using a console.log. In other hand, more serious bugs, must require debugging tools with breakpoints and all the good stuff.\nAnswer: That\'s great. Can you tell me about a time when you had to optimize the load time or performance of a website or application? What techniques did you use?\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: Sure. Firstly, I try to keep the JS bundle as minimal. One strategy might be static site generation, for examples. After that, I might go into more granular things. For instance, I would audit the page using tools like lighthouse to see each resources are affecting the performance. In other words, I would measure things first before making any changes. Of course, I\'m talking about measuring performance in a production code.\nAnswer: Those are great techniques. Can you tell me about any experience you have with responsive design?\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: Definitely. Most of the project I work on need to look great in pretty much any screen size - From mobile viewports, to desktop, up to large iMacs. Therefore, responsive design is must have. I also use fluid typography which reduce the need of media queries in some cases.\nAnswer: That\'s great. Last question, Can you tell me about a time when you had to implement a design that you didn\'t agree with? How did you approach the situation? [/INST]', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=0, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=100, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None, extra_args=None), prompt_token_ids: None, prompt_embeds shape: None, lora_request: None, prompt_adapter_request: None.
